label("$C$",C,S);
label("$D$",D,NW);
label("$E$",E,S);
label("$3$",(A+C)/2,S);
label("$8$",(B+D)/2,NE);
label("$5$",(A+E)/2,S);
[/asy]

Since the diagonals of a kite are perpendicular, we have that $\overline{CD}$ is the altitude of right triangle $ACE$.  The area of triangle $ACE$ is $\frac{1}{2}\cdot AC\cdot AE=\frac{1}{2}\cdot 3\cdot 5=\frac{15}{2}$.  Since $\overline{CD}$ is the altitude to the base $\overline{AE}$, we have that \[\frac{1}{2}\cdot CD\cdot AE=\frac{15}{2}.\]Solving, we find that $CD=\boxed{3}$.  I hope it is correct.

